WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.880
Hi, my name is Andy Tucher and I'm a Package Developer Educator on the Tidyverse team at

00:00:09.880 --> 00:00:10.880
Posit.

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:16.240
I'll be teaching a workshop at the upcoming Posit Conf in Chicago called Fundamentals

00:00:16.240 --> 00:00:20.520
of Package Development and I wanted to give you the top three reasons why I think you

00:00:20.520 --> 00:00:22.639
might want to join us at the workshop.

00:00:22.639 --> 00:00:25.160
The first is just getting started.

00:00:25.160 --> 00:00:29.440
You might have an idea for a package already but don't really know where to start or you

00:00:29.440 --> 00:00:32.639
might have done some package development before but feel like you could use some help

00:00:32.639 --> 00:00:35.080
being a bit more efficient about it.

00:00:35.080 --> 00:00:39.360
The workshop will be an interactive and hopefully fun run through of the package development

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:40.360
process.

00:00:40.360 --> 00:00:45.400
We'll be live coding together and building an R package from scratch and along the way

00:00:45.400 --> 00:00:49.959
learning the basic moving parts of an R package.

00:00:49.959 --> 00:00:53.160
The second reason is to learn good and easy practices.

00:00:53.160 --> 00:00:56.439
You'll learn the tools and techniques that the Tidyverse team have developed and use

00:00:56.439 --> 00:00:58.439
in their day to day work.

00:00:58.439 --> 00:01:02.959
These practices really smooth off the rough edges of the package development process and

00:01:02.959 --> 00:01:06.879
help prevent you from many of the common pitfalls you might encounter.

00:01:06.879 --> 00:01:11.199
They are designed to help you fall into a pit of success instead.

00:01:11.199 --> 00:01:15.800
Using these tools helps you build a workflow that gets the esoteric details of package

00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:19.720
structure out of the way and helps you focus on the content.

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:24.199
And third, just to help you get better at R. You might simply be looking for that next

00:01:24.199 --> 00:01:28.120
step in your R programming journey and want to build some new skills.

00:01:28.120 --> 00:01:32.519
If you feel like you've plateaued in developing your R skills, learning package development

00:01:32.519 --> 00:01:38.919
can be a great next step in moving along in the continuum from data analysis to building

00:01:38.919 --> 00:01:44.279
tools for yourself and other people and also to start to learn how and when to apply software

00:01:44.279 --> 00:01:46.800
engineering principles to your work.

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:50.760
So if any of these points or all of these points resonate with you, I hope that you'll

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:53.879
join us at our workshop at conf and I hope to see you there.

00:01:53.879 --> 00:01:54.379
Thanks.

